# Line-ending policy. Without this, the Windows Git client
# (`core.autocrlf=true`) silently converts LF to CRLF on checkout,
# which breaks the GitHub Actions YAML parser when the workflow
# file ends up with mixed line endings. The CI had been failing
# instantly on every push until I caught the mixed-CRLF issue in
# b8d8bba; this file prevents the next contributor on a Windows
# machine from re-introducing it.
#
# Pattern: declare LF as the canonical line ending for everything
# that matters to the build, with a few specific overrides for
# files that genuinely need CRLF (none in this repo, but the
# .bat / .cmd escape hatch is here for the day someone adds one).
*               text=auto eol=lf
*.bat           text eol=crlf
*.cmd           text eol=crlf
*.ps1           text eol=crlf
*.sh            text eol=lf

# Dart source —LF (Dart formatter emits LF; the analyzer is
# CRLF-tolerant but the linter and CI formatters assume LF).
*.dart          text eol=lf

# YAML —must be LF for GitHub Actions; mixed line endings
# silently break the Actions YAML parser (see b8d8bba).
*.yml           text eol=lf
*.yaml          text eol=lf

# JSON —LF; the L10n JSON files in assets/l10n/ are committed
# as LF and any CRLF injection would break json.load().
*.json          text eol=lf

# Markdown —LF.
*.md            text eol=lf

# Plain text —LF.
*.txt           text eol=lf

# Lockfiles —must be LF for `pub get` to parse.
pubspec.lock    text eol=lf

# Images, fonts, and other binary assets —never re-encode.
*.png           binary
*.jpg           binary
*.jpeg          binary
*.gif           binary
*.webp          binary
*.ico           binary
*.ttf           binary
*.otf           binary
*.woff           binary
*.woff2          binary